This paper is the final project for Prof. Paul Shaman’s course Econometrics I (STAT 520) in Fall 2016. The direct inspiration for this work is the paper of İ. Semih Akçomak, Dinand Webbink and Bas ter Weel (hereon “Authors”), which appears in Volume 126 of The Economic Journal (June 2016, DOI: 10.1111/ecoj.12193. The less-direct inspiration is a personal interest in Dutch history and culture, as well as the possibility of my enrollment in graduate study at Leiden (Classics & Ancient History) come Fall 2017.

1 The Problem

It is a wide-ranging and highly impressive historical study, examining the formation of a 14th-century Christian order as a means to assess (quantitatively!) conventional wisdom surrounding the rapid rise of Northern European prosperity: Was it Protestant ethic? Dutch shrewdness? The Hanseatic League? Less glamorously, the Authors posit that it was due to a religious order that encouraged literacy and urban living.

2 The Data

There are three sets of data provided by the authors:

growth: fairly detailed data (population sizes, book production share, literacy in 1860, distances, religious-activity dummy variables) for 67 Dutch cities

literacy: more-detailed literacy data (1600, 1675, 1750) and distances for 33 Dutch cities

hinterland: geographic and population data for 91 Dutch, Belgian, and German cities

2.1 Independent Variables

The Authors’ investigation was ultimately one of historical causality: What was the (quantitative) impact of the Brethren of the Common Life? For a religous movement to be ‘affiliated’ with a city, they decided that it must have a monastery, school, hostel, or other movement-affiliated institution located within 5 kilometers, or about an hour’s walk.

BCL_presence: Was there a BCL institution located within 5 km?

BCL_number: How many BCL institutions were located within 5 km?

While BCL_number may give a better sense of the ‘intensity’ of the movement’s involvement in a given community, it is also more liable to bias by a municipality’s population, wealth, and resources. A bigger city could accommodate more institutions, or a smaller city may lack a public school and support BCL-founded education. Regardless, analysis will be performed for both independent variables.

2.2 Dependent Variables

There are three dependent variables, attempting to show a mixture of human and economic capital. These might be be related or prerequisite to a common understanding of commercial development, as it occurred in the Low Countries during the 16th and 17th centuries.

Book_share is the percentage of total Low Country bookeditions (2,378 in the Netherlands and Belgium between 1470 and 1500) produced in a given city before 1500.

Literacy (male, 1600): percentage of bridegrooms from a given city (33 available) who signed name on marriage registration instead of stamping fingerprint; 12,152 total observations at the Amsterdam Archives. Literacy (male, 1860) is data collected from 19th-century birth registers in the Historical Sample of the Netherlands (HSN), aggregated by authors from provinces to municipalities.

City growth (1400-1560) for 67 cities with 1,000 or more residents in 1400. Most population estimates are the work of recent scholars, from whom the Authors took the most relevant and compelling figures. Given the disparities between municipalities and centuries–rapid growth overall and especially in urban areas following the agricultural and industrial revolutions–it makes sense to use the logarithm of population percentage change.

2.3 Exogenous Variables

There are a number of variables that, while (ideally) uncorrelated with the independent variable, may have influence over the dependent variable. It is necessary to include these in the more-robust regression procedures in order to control for their confounding impact, thereby isolating the partial effect of BCL affiliation.

Schools_before_1400: Proxy for a city’s educational infrastructure prior to and independent of BCL affiliation

*Population_1300; _1400; growth_1300_1400*: Control for the impact of city size and prior urbanization trends upon the growth 1400-1560

The presence of other major religous orders. The five largest Dutch monastic movements were Modern Devotion (which included BCL), Tertiarians, Franciscans, Beghards and Beguines, and Cistercians.

Other proxy variables for economic potential and wherewithal: location on a river or seaport; distance to a Roman colony or road (trade route); membership or affiliation with the Hanseatic League (international trade). Distances to various cities also factor in as needed; for instance, any regression attempting to explain literacy should include Distance_to_Amsterdam, since all literacy records before the 19th century are from the Amsterdam Archives and might be biased toward those cities closer to Amsterdam.

2.4 Summary Statistics

The following table includes means, standard deviations, and two-sample t-test P-values for the dependent, instrumental, and exogenous variables in each of the two crucial samples: those Dutch cities unaffiliated with the Brethren of the Common Life (BCL=0), and those affiliated (BCL=1). [Cf. Authors’ Table 4, p. 841] The t-tests are two-tailed; that is, the null hypothesis for each variable is the difference between BCL and non-BCL cities should be trivial in either direction.

2.5 Discussion: Book Share

Book production is a good national metric for cultural capital and economic development. Estimates of per capita gross-domestic product in Western European nation-regions, reflecting scholars’ direct claims about economic wellbeing, are plotted against per capita book edition printing in the same nation-regions. Here for 1500:

The two per capita variables, representing human and economic capital, have a correlation of 0.901.

Notes: Per the authors [p. 834], population and per-capita GDP numbers are taken from Maddison Project. The number of book editions is taken from Incunabula Short Title Catalogue of British Library. Unfortunately, no GDP estimates are available for France before 1820 (at which point they are rather detailed), even though France and French-speaking Switzerland contain 5,437 book editions and 15.3 million people (over a quarter of Western Europe) by 1500. The book publication figures group together Germany with German-speaking Austria and Switzerland, although GDP figures are only available for the first. The same is true of Spain and Portugal, although only the former has a GDP estimate for 1500; Portugal’s tends to be higher than Spain’s (from 1550 on, and probably earlier due to its earlier Reconquista), but the Spanish estimate (probably too low) was used for both.

Of course, only a handful of municipalities are responsible for most of the printing in a given nation. This unfortunately means that book_share is not a particularly useful metric for representing human-capital differences inter urbis.

Only five of those cities with nonzero book production also appear in the Amsterdam Archives data offering literacy in 1600. Comparing book_share and literacy among those five:

These cities are nontrivial, having significant populations and the oldest university in the Netherlands (Leiden, 1575). The correlation between book publication (1470-1500) and literacy (1600) in the five cities is 0.774, which is rather strong. The sample is simply too small to achieve a statistically significant OLS estimator, working with only 3 degrees of freedom.

While I am hesitant to give book production the same weight as the authors did, it is satisfying to know that there are strong correlations between this variable, national per capita GDP, and city-by-city literacy rates. Going forward, I will retain the dependent variables population growth and literacy rates as the two twin markers of economic growth and human capital development, respectively.

3 The Models (OLS + 2SLS)

While the problem seems simple on its face – comparing proxy variables between two samples to draw conclusions about economic development – the ‘treatment’ of BCL presence was not, in a sense, randomly assigned. The Modern Devotion movement did not conduct double-blind trials in a random sample of Dutch cities. BCL affiliation needs to be independent of ‘error’ in the analysis due to measurement, treatment, or historical fluctuations.

Following this rationale, the Authors opt for a Two-Stage Least Squares approach using an Instrumental Variable, in line with scholarship attempting historical causality. In this case, since Geert Groote founded the BCL movement in Deventer, the scholars use “distance from Deventer” as the instrument. BCL affiliation insofar as new houses would be formed, most likely, in cities with geographical proximity; priests and brothers would train or visit Deventer, as it became a site of the broader Modern Devotion movement. That said, there is nothing in the Groote’s biography to suggest that he founded BCL in Deventer for any particular, local reason. It was a reasonably populous city with an intellectual climate, but among all options (e.g. Utrecht, Nigmegen, Haarlem, Leiden) its initial BCL ‘treatment’ was effectively random. In both senses, then, Distance_from_Deventer should be both relevant and exogenous – that is, correlated with BCL affiliation and uncorrelated with any exogenous variables controlled for the 2SLS procedure.

One criticism is the Authors’ use of ‘as-the-crow-flies’ geometric distances. While this is understandable and perhaps unavoidable, land travel in the medieval world was highly difficult, and it is highly unlikely that a journey’s distance and time were linearly related.

3.1 Instrument Relevance

For OLS estimators, the number listed is the partial slope, with its associated P-value in parantheses.

The likelihood of BCL presence and the number of BCL institutions decrease with greater distance from Deventer, so it passes the test of relevance.

3.2 Instrument Exogeneity

It is only useful to test exogeneity against variable phenomena which predate BCL’s founding in Deventer. While distance from Deventer is certainly correlated with 16th-century urbanization and literacy rates in 1600, we use earlier population figures and the school presence proxy to test Deventer’s historical independence. While it is useful to include population figures in the robust regressions, only 15 of 67 cities have population estimates in 1300. The 1300-1400 trendline is still important for controlling population growth 1400-1560, so the numbers are included also in testing the exogeneity of the instrument.

Unsurprisingly, the Modern Devotion affiliation is correlated with BCL affiliation, as are the Beghards and Beguines. Since the interest overall is in the influence of contemporary religious movements, and since they shared some institutional frameworks, this is expected.

Otherwise, only the Hanseatic League is significant in regression with Distance_to_Deventer. The Authors spend a section of their paper repeating all 2SLS procedures with control for the Hanse dummy variable – essentially, one more variable in the regression, or splitting the sample and performing the same procedure on Hanseatic and non-Hanseatic cities – but I am unconcerned for a few reasons:

  • The correlation between Distance_to_Deventer and Hanse is only -0.254, which is not particularly high.
  • The Hanseatic League had unclear membership criteria (full member, trading partner, non-aggression signatory, etc.), so the Authors had to make some educated guesses.
  • In its early form, the League essentially mapped a geographic region: some northeastern Dutch, northwest German, and southern Scandinavian cities. Since Deventer is in the northeastern quadrant of the Netherlands, it makes sense that two geographic variables are correlated.
  • Membership in the Hanseatic League, while important for import-export figures, probably did not have any (potentially confounding) impact upon literacy rates or even urbanization, which are the proxies for human-capital development in this study. (Indeed the Authors went on to prove that Hanse did not have a significant partial slope in OLS for any dependent variable.)

Given the results of the two tests, Distance_to_Deventer is both relevant and exogenous for instrumental use. The Authors go further, devoting a section to placebo testing – i.e. testing distances to other Dutch cities, with insignificant results – to prove the singular benefit of the instrument.

4 Results + Interpretation

4.1 Literacy in 1600

The depedent variable is male literacy in 1600. For the sake of comparison, regressions are shown both with and without instrumentation. Exogenous variables are Log_Population_1400 (under presumption that a city’s prior size might affect its prior literacy rate) and Distance_to_Amsterdam (as mentioned above, literacy data collection may skew toward Greater Amsterdam).

4.2 Population Growth, 1400-1560

The depedent variable is population growth, 1400-1560. For the sake of comparison, regressions are shown both with and without instrumentation. Exogenous variables are Log_Population_1400 (under presumption that a city’s prior size might affect its potential growth), Sea and River (as the 15th-16th century marked the beginning of seafaring mercantile prosperity), and Roman (since Roman settlement status denotes an older, more-established municipality).

The Authors note that population growth was, at that time, related closely to economic potential – “a post-Malthusian regiume in which human capital translates into population growth.” [p. 848] They also reestimated the full OLS model, excluding cities that grew or shrank more than 100% in the 160-year period. [Note: Since a city that loses 100% of its population would have stopped existing, the Authors just excluded those cities that grew rapidly.]

4.3 Growth in Greater Netherlands

Using data from correspondence and monastic records, we can also include 12 Belgian and 12 German cities alongside the 67 Dutch ones. The only indepedent variable for these is BCL affiliation, since there is no reliable metric for measuring the number of instutions in the additional cities. (The Authors note that there is only information available for larger cities, especially in Germany, even though BCL set up institutions in several smaller ones.) This is the same analysis as before,

4.4 Effect Diminishment

Literacy rates in 1860 are more reliable, available for all cities, and in all likelihood unaffected by BCL instutions present centuries earlier. What we will test for instead, out of academic curiosity, is the percentage of Protestants in a city. After the Reformation, the Netherlands became a haven for Calvinists, Reformed, and some Anabaptists, all of whom put significant emphasis on literacy.

As expected, the partial effect of BCL affiliation has ‘worn away’ by the 19th century, while share of Protestants is both significant and nontrivial.

# 3.1 Instrument Relevance

ivtest <- function(var,iv="d_d_1",data=growth) {
  c(
    "Correlation" = round(cor(data[,var],data[,iv]),3),
    "OLS_Estimate" = paste(paste(round(summary(
      lm(data[,iv]~data[,var])
    )$coefficients[2,c(1,4)],3),collapse=" ("),")",sep=""),
    "n" = length(growth$bcl_x)
  )
}

df <- rbind(
  "BCL_presence"=ivtest("bcl_x"),
  "BCL_number"=ivtest("bcl_n")
)

grid.arrange(tableGrob(df,theme=tt))

coefs <- function(model) {
  df <- summary(model)$coefficients
  paste(round(df[,1],3)," (",round(df[,4],3),")",sep="")
}

vec <- c(rep("",9))

vectorize <- function(model,cfs,F_st=FALSE,R_sq=TRUE) {
  vec[cfs] <- coefs(model) # where the variable partial slopes should go in table
  vec[length(vec)-2] <- sum(summary(model)$df[c(1:2)]) # number of observations, vars + df
  vec[length(vec)-1] <- if(F_st==TRUE) { round(summary(model)$fstatistic[1],3) } else { "" }
  vec[length(vec)] <- if(R_sq==TRUE) { round(summary(model)$r.squared,3) } else { "" }
  vec
}

df <- data.frame(cbind(
  vectorize(model1,c(6,1)),
  vectorize(model2,c(6,1,4,5)),
  vectorize(model3,c(6,2,4,5)),

  vectorize(model5,c(6,1),R_sq=F),

# 4.4 Effect Diminishment

model1 <- lm(xlit4080~bcl_x,data=growth)
model2 <- lm(xlit4080~bcl_x+lpop1400,data=growth)
model3 <- lm(xlit4080~bcl_x+lpop1400+sea+river+d_roman,data=growth)
model4 <- lm(xlit4080~bcl_x+mprotw+lpop1400+sea+river+d_roman,data=growth)
model5 <- lm(bcl_x~d_d_1,data=growth)
model6 <- ivreg(xlit4080~bcl_x|d_d_1,data=growth)
model7 <- lm(bcl_x~d_d_1+mprotw+lpop1400+sea+river+d_roman,data=growth100)
model8 <- ivreg(xlit4080~bcl_x+mprotw+lpop1400+sea+river+d_roman|d_d_1+mprotw+lpop1400+sea+river+d_roman,data=growth100)

vec <- rep("",11)

df <- data.frame(cbind(
  vectorize(model1,c(8,1)),
  vectorize(model2,c(8,1,4)),
  vectorize(model3,c(8,1,4,5,6,7)),
  vectorize(model4,c(8,1,3,4,5,6,7)),
  vectorize(model5,c(8,2),F_st=T),
  vectorize(model6,c(8,1)),
  vectorize(model7,c(8,2,3,4,5,6,7),F_st=T),
  vectorize(model8,c(8,1,3,4,5,6,7))),
  row.names=c("BCL_presence","Dist_Deventer","Share_Protestants","Log_pop_1400","Sea","River","Roman","Constant","Observations","F_statistic","R_squared")
); names(df) <- c(rep("OLS_Lit",4),rep(c("1st_BCLx","2SLS"),2))

tt7 <- ttheme_minimal(
  base_size = 9,
  core = list(bg_params=list(fill=c("white","grey")[c(2,rep(1,10))]))
)

grid.arrange(tableGrob(df,theme=tt7),top="Literacy Rates in 1860")
